\section{Motivation: beyond collapse language}\label{sec:motivation}

The standard quantum-mechanical vocabulary calls the resolution of an
indeterminate state into a definite outcome \emph{wavefunction collapse}
or \emph{measurement}. This vocabulary names the event without saying
what it is. The Born rule supplies probabilities; the projection
postulate supplies an after-state; neither supplies a mechanism. A
century of measurement-problem literature attests to how persistent
this gap is.

Several research programmes have attempted to close the gap by
identifying an underlying physical or geometric process for state
selection. Penrose~\cite{Penrose1996} proposed that gravitational
self-energy of mass-energy superpositions sets a threshold above which
state reduction occurs objectively, independent of any observer. The
Penrose--Hameroff extension~\cite{PenroseHameroff1996} situates this Objective Reduction
(\emph{OR}) inside biological microtubules. We take Penrose OR as a
\emph{neighbouring} attempt to identify a geometry-coupled mechanism
for state selection: not an opponent, not a falsified model, and not a
target of refutation, but a precedent that establishes the
\emph{shape} of the question we are trying to answer.

Independently, the Vibrational Field Dynamics (VFD) programme has
identified a finite geometric substrate --- the binary icosahedral
group $2I$ together with its 600-cell vertex graph $\Vsub$ --- whose
spectral, algebraic, and operator structure recurs in passive response
phenomena \cite{AriaClosureKernel, SmartBAnomaly}, in active selection
dynamics \cite{SmartTransportLaw, SmartACT}, in cognitive substrate
witnesses \cite{SmartARIAChess}, and in the spectral structure of the
Standard Model mass spectrum \cite{SmartV, SmartVRev}. The recurrence
is not narrative: it is structurally enforced at the operator level
(the closure-response operator $\Cphi = L_M + \pphi^{-2} I$ on $\Vsub$
satisfies $\|\Cphi^{-1}\| = \pphi^2$ exactly; see Appendix~\ref{app:field-signature-audit}~E)
and at the eigenvalue level ($\Vsub$'s Laplacian has a 78.3\%
$\sigma$-fixed spectral fraction; see Appendix~\ref{app:field-signature-audit}~A).

Across these regimes the same operational pattern appears: a field
state arrives at a layer of the substrate where it cannot maintain a
coherent projection; the unresolved mismatch propagates inward through
nested layers; resolution occurs by selection of a closure-compatible
attractor geometry. This paper names that pattern, gives it a single
mechanism statement, formalises it at the level of a rung-indexed
closure residual, and positions the existing programme literature as
case studies under a shared-mechanism hypothesis rather than as
separate phenomena.

The framing is restrained on purpose. We do not propose a replacement
for quantum mechanics. We do not derive measurement probabilities; the
Born rule remains the input. We do not refute Penrose OR; we generalise
its core move (geometry-coupled state selection) from a single
gravitational threshold to a stratified projection cascade. We do not
claim cascade closure as an empirically completed theorem of physics;
it is an organising mechanism whose individual mathematical components
are imported from earlier papers in the programme at sharply scoped
epistemic flags. The contribution of this paper is the mechanism
statement and the projection-class reading, not new physical results.

A reader familiar only with the measurement-problem literature should
expect to gain: a single name for a recurring operational pattern; a
finite geometric substrate on which the pattern can be made
mathematically explicit; and a placement of several open
mainstream-mathematics problems --- including the Riemann Hypothesis,
Yang--Mills mass gap, Birch--Swinnerton-Dyer, and the others
(\S\ref{sec:millennium}) --- as instances of the same projection-class
mechanism. The placement is hypothesis-labelled and does not constitute
proof of any of those problems.

\section{Core mechanism: instability, cascade, crystallisation}\label{sec:mechanism}

\subsection{The triad}

We organise the mechanism around a three-stage operational triad:

\begin{equation}\label{eq:triad}
   \text{Instability} \;\longrightarrow\; \text{Cascade} \;\longrightarrow\; \text{Crystallisation}.
\end{equation}

These are not distinct physical processes. They are three views of one
resolution event: the external view (collapse, often coarse-grained
into a probability statement), the propagation view (cascade, the
substrate-level dynamics between instability onset and resolution),
and the internal view (crystallisation, the selection of a definite
attractor geometry). The vocabulary distinction matters because it
locates where in the triad each existing programme paper sits: the
closure-response operator and its passive witnesses
\cite{AriaClosureKernel, SmartBAnomaly} characterise the substrate
on which cascade dynamics occur; the active-selection literature
\cite{SmartTransportLaw, SmartACT} describes the cascade itself; the
spectral mass spectrum \cite{SmartV, SmartVRev} records the
crystallised attractors.

\subsection{The closure-residual functional}

Let the substrate be a finite (possibly stratified) set of
\emph{rungs} indexed by $k \in \{0, 1, \ldots, N\}$. At each rung
the substrate exposes a geometric carrier $G_k$ (a graph, polytope,
algebra, lattice, or projection class); the carrier comes equipped
with a closure-residual functional
\begin{equation}\label{eq:Rk}
   R_k : \Phi_k \longrightarrow [0, \infty),
\end{equation}
where $\Phi_k$ is the space of admissible field states on $G_k$. The
functional measures the failure of $\Phi_k$ to be closure-compatible
with the rung-$k$ projection. Closure-compatibility means $R_k(\Phi_k) = 0$.
The construction of $R_k$ at finite levels is given by the closure
functional and gradient operator of \cite{CascadeClosureDynamics};
the underlying refinement state spaces and bonding maps are given
by \cite{CascadeRefinementSpaces}.

\begin{definition}[Cascade closure]\label{def:cascade-closure}
A cascade-closure event on the rung sequence $(G_0, \ldots, G_N)$ is
a triple $(\Phi, R, \pi)$ consisting of an admissible field state
$\Phi = (\Phi_0, \ldots, \Phi_N)$, the closure-residual functional
$R$ defined rung-wise as in \eqref{eq:Rk}, and a sequence of
admissible projection maps
$\pi_{k+1, k} : G_{k+1} \to G_k$ such that the flow induced by the
gradient operator of $R$ relative to $\pi$ converges to a fixed point
$\Phi^\star$ with $R_k(\Phi^\star_k) = 0$ for all $k$. The fixed
point $\Phi^\star$ is the \emph{crystallised} state.
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}[Vocabulary]\label{rem:vocabulary}
Within Definition~\ref{def:cascade-closure}, the three views map onto
the triad as follows: \emph{instability} is the condition $R_k(\Phi) > 0$
on at least one rung; \emph{cascade} is the gradient flow of $R$
through the projection sequence $\pi$; \emph{crystallisation} is the
fixed-point selection of $\Phi^\star$. \emph{Collapse}, in the
Born-rule sense, is the external coarse-graining of this fixed-point
selection; the cascade-closure framework does not modify the Born
rule and does not derive measurement probabilities.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}[Status of Definition~\ref{def:cascade-closure}]\label{rem:def-status}
Definition~\ref{def:cascade-closure} is the paper's organising
definition, not a theorem of physics. The convergence-to-fixed-point
clause is part of the \emph{definition of the closure event}: a triple
that does not converge to a residual-zero fixed point is not a
cascade-closure event in the sense of this paper. We do not claim that
arbitrary $(\Phi, R, \pi)$ triples on arbitrary rung sequences
necessarily admit such convergence; the claim that any specific rung
sequence does admit it is a separate statement that requires
\emph{additional} hypotheses (e.g.\ Hypotheses~\ref{hyp:refinement-int}
and~\ref{hyp:monotone} of \S\ref{sec:rung-model}, conditional
Proposition~\ref{prop:resid-comp}). The existence of the gradient flow
at finite levels, energy descent, and refinement compatibility are
imported from \cite{CascadeClosureDynamics} (Theorem
\texttt{thm:gradient-operator}, Proposition
\texttt{prop:energy-dissipation}, Theorem
\texttt{thm:coercive-contraction}). The four-phase comonadic cycle
that justifies treating the triad as a single resolution event is
imported from \cite{CascadeCapstone} (Section
\texttt{sec:comonad}, Claim \texttt{claim:four-phase-realisation},
Remark \texttt{rmk:comonad-status}); that import is conditional on the
named hypotheses inside the capstone preprint and is not re-proved here.
\end{remark}

\subsection{What the substrate does and does not contribute}

The substrate $\Vsub$ does the following work in the mechanism: it
fixes the carrier set on which the rung-$0$ closure residual is
defined, it supplies the operator $\Cphi = L_M + \pphi^{-2} I$ whose
inverse norm controls the relaxation rate (Appendix~\ref{app:field-signature-audit}~E),
it carries the spectral structure that determines which projection
classes are admissible (Appendix~\ref{app:field-signature-audit}~A),
and through the icosian / $H_4$ Coxeter symmetry it constrains which
attractor geometries can crystallise. It does \emph{not}, by itself,
do the following: select a unique attractor without dynamical input;
predict observer-dependent outcomes; or supply the projection axiom
that links spectral structure to specific analytic objects (such
links are framework-level hypotheses; see \S\ref{sec:millennium}).
The honest-negatives in
Appendix~\ref{app:field-signature-audit}~A,~E mark the substrate's
boundary explicitly: $\sigma$-fixed eigenvectors do not preferentially
localise on the binary tetrahedral subgroup $2T$, and $\pphi$-cocycle
edge weightings of the kernel underperform the unweighted variant.
We treat both as constraints on what may be claimed.

\section{Rung model and residual propagation}\label{sec:rung-model}

\subsection{Rungs, projections, and admissible states}

Each rung $k$ carries a triple $(G_k, \Phi_k, R_k)$ where $G_k$ is a
geometric carrier, $\Phi_k$ a space of admissible field states, and
$R_k$ a closure residual as in \eqref{eq:Rk}. The full rung sequence
$(G_0, \ldots, G_N)$ is connected by admissible projection maps
\begin{equation}\label{eq:projection-map}
   \pi_{k+1, k} : G_{k+1} \longrightarrow G_k,
\end{equation}
required to be refinement-compatible in the sense of
\cite{CascadeClosureDynamics} (Definition~\texttt{def:refinement-compat}).
For each $k$ we write
\begin{equation}\label{eq:pushforward}
   \pi_{k+1, k}^{\sharp} : \Phi_{k+1} \longrightarrow \Phi_k
\end{equation}
for the induced pushforward (or marginalisation) on field states,
following the same direction as the underlying geometric projection.
For composite high-to-low projection across $j$ rungs we write
$\pi_{N, k}^{\sharp} := \pi_{k+1, k}^{\sharp} \circ \cdots \circ \pi_{N, N-1}^{\sharp}$.
In the mass-only finite-level construction of
\cite{CascadeClosureDynamics} (Theorem~\texttt{thm:flow-intertwining}),
$\pi^{\sharp}$ intertwines the closure flow at adjacent rungs;
outside the mass-only case the intertwining is retained here as
Hypothesis~\ref{hyp:refinement-int} below. The finite-level Hilbert
and bonding machinery on which the mass-only result rests is supplied
by \cite{CascadeRefinementSpaces}
(Theorems~\texttt{thm:bonding},~\texttt{thm:commute}).

The rung indexing is not metaphysical. In the cascade programme it is
realised concretely as the cascade-derivation rung sequence catalogued
in \cite{CascadeFoundations} and \cite{CascadeCapstone}: an arithmetic
coefficient layer $\Q(\pphi)$ \cite{CascadeSigmaRat}, the 12D meta
layer $L_{12} = E_8 \oplus \Z[\pphi]^4$ \cite{Cascade12D, CascadeMetaLayer},
the algebraic substrate (icosian $H_4$, $D_4$, $\Vsub$, $V_{24}$, octonions)
\cite{CascadeAlgSubstrate}, the refinement state spaces \cite{CascadeRefinementSpaces},
the closure-dynamics layer \cite{CascadeClosureDynamics}, and the
metric / hydrodynamic / spectral / observer projection classes
\cite{CascadeMetricProj, CascadeSchlafli, CascadeHydroProj, ObserverInstance}.
Section~\ref{sec:rung-table} resolves each layer to its source and
epistemic status.

\subsection{Conditional residual compositionality}\label{ssec:residual-comp}

The mechanism statement in \eqref{eq:triad} requires that closure
compatibility \emph{compose} along the rung path: if each adjacent
projection is closure-compatible and the rungwise residuals interact
monotonically with the projection maps, then the global field
composition lies on the closure-fixed locus. We state this as a
conditional lemma; the conditions are not generically satisfied and
must be verified per case.

\begin{hypothesis}[Pointwise refinement-intertwining]\label{hyp:refinement-int}
For the rung sequence $(G_0, \ldots, G_N)$ and projections
$(\pi_{k+1, k})_{k}$, assume that for every $k$ the rungwise gradient
operator $\nabla R_k$ commutes with $\pi^{\sharp}_{k+1, k}$ in the sense of
\cite{CascadeClosureDynamics} Definition~\texttt{def:refinement-compat}.
\end{hypothesis}

\begin{hypothesis}[Monotonicity]\label{hyp:monotone}
For every $k$ and every $\Phi_{k+1} \in \Phi_{k+1}$,
$R_k(\pi^{\sharp}_{k+1, k} \Phi_{k+1}) \leq R_{k+1}(\Phi_{k+1})$.
\end{hypothesis}

\begin{proposition}[Conditional closure-residual compositionality]\label{prop:resid-comp}
Under Hypotheses~\ref{hyp:refinement-int} and~\ref{hyp:monotone}, if
the gradient flow of $R_N$ on $G_N$ converges to a fixed point
$\Phi^\star_N$ with $R_N(\Phi^\star_N) = 0$, then the projected
states $\Phi^\star_k := \pi^{\sharp}_{N, k} \Phi^\star_N$ satisfy
both
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2.4em, label=\textup{(\arabic*)}]
\item $R_k(\Phi^\star_k) = 0$ for all $k \leq N$, and
\item $\Phi^\star_k$ is a fixed point of the rung-$k$ gradient flow,
for all $k \leq N$ at which Hypothesis~\ref{hyp:refinement-int}
applies.
\end{enumerate}
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}[Proof sketch]
By induction downward from $k = N$. The base case $k = N$ is the
hypothesis $R_N(\Phi^\star_N) = 0$ and the assumption that
$\Phi^\star_N$ is a rung-$N$ fixed point. For the inductive step,
suppose $R_{k+1}(\Phi^\star_{k+1}) = 0$ and that $\Phi^\star_{k+1}$
is a rung-$(k{+}1)$ fixed point, where
$\Phi^\star_{k+1} := \pi^{\sharp}_{N, k+1} \Phi^\star_N$.
\emph{For (1):} by Hypothesis~\ref{hyp:monotone},
$R_k(\Phi^\star_k) = R_k(\pi^{\sharp}_{k+1, k} \Phi^\star_{k+1})
\leq R_{k+1}(\Phi^\star_{k+1}) = 0$, and $R_k \geq 0$, so
$R_k(\Phi^\star_k) = 0$.
\emph{For (2):} by Hypothesis~\ref{hyp:refinement-int},
$\pi^{\sharp}_{k+1, k}$ commutes with the adjacent-rung gradient flow
at the level supported by \cite{CascadeClosureDynamics}
Theorem~\texttt{thm:flow-intertwining}, so the image of a rung-$(k{+}1)$
fixed point under $\pi^{\sharp}_{k+1, k}$ is a rung-$k$ fixed point.
The composite identity $\pi^{\sharp}_{N, k} = \pi^{\sharp}_{k+1, k}
\circ \pi^{\sharp}_{N, k+1}$ makes the induction well-defined.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}[Conditional status]\label{rem:resid-comp-status}
Proposition~\ref{prop:resid-comp} is conditional on
Hypotheses~\ref{hyp:refinement-int} and~\ref{hyp:monotone}; both must
be checked per rung sequence. Hypothesis~\ref{hyp:refinement-int} is
known in the mass-only P3/P4 finite-level construction
\cite{CascadeRefinementSpaces, CascadeClosureDynamics}; outside that
case it is retained here as a hypothesis and not discharged.
Hypothesis~\ref{hyp:monotone} is a structural assumption on the choice
of rung-wise residuals and is not automatic. Failure of either
hypothesis at a particular rung means the cascade does \emph{not}
compose at that step, and external resolution by intermediate
absorption or by attractor selection at a lower rung is required.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Failure modes and resolution paths}

When Proposition~\ref{prop:resid-comp} fails at rung $k$, two
resolution paths remain: \emph{intermediate absorption}, in which the
residual $R_k$ is reduced by an intervention internal to the rung-$k$
substrate without propagation downward (the active-selection regime
of \cite{SmartTransportLaw, SmartACT}); or \emph{attractor selection},
in which the cascade flow projects directly onto a low-rung fixed
point that absorbs the residual at the cost of state information
(the spectral mass-projection regime of \cite{SmartV, SmartVRev}).
These two paths are not exhaustive but they cover the empirically
documented cases in the programme literature. Section~\ref{sec:case-studies}
revisits each.

\section{Geometry identification across rungs}\label{sec:rung-table}

This section assembles the central rung table of the paper. Each row
resolves a layer of the cascade-closure mechanism to a specific
geometric carrier $G_k$ together with an epistemic flag stating
whether the carrier and its role are theorem-grade, model-chosen,
imported under conditional hypothesis, or interpretive. No row
introduces a new mathematical claim; every entry imports its
substantive content from a named source in the audited dependency
list of the work order
(\texttt{papers/cascade-mechanism/WO-CASCADE-MECHANISM.md}~\S3).

\subsection{Reading conventions}

In Table~\ref{tab:rungs} the column \emph{status} carries one of:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
\item \textsf{[Th-imp]} --- imported theorem from a cited source paper.
\item \textsf{[Pr-imp]} --- imported proposition.
\item \textsf{[Hyp-imp]} --- imported under a named conditional hypothesis;
  the citation tracks the hypothesis label inside the source.
\item \textsf{[Mod]} --- model choice within the cascade-mechanism
  framework; not derived in this paper, not derived elsewhere as a
  uniqueness theorem.
\item \textsf{[Int]} --- interpretive use of structural material from
  a programme document; not load-bearing for any formal claim in this
  paper.
\end{itemize}

A row's \emph{status} is determined by the source, not by the present
paper. We do not upgrade an imported hypothesis to a theorem; we do
not downgrade an imported theorem to a hypothesis. Sources are cited
exactly as they label themselves.

