\end{longtable}

\subsection{What the table earns and does not earn}

The table earns three things. First, every entry is sourced; no row
relies on cascade-mechanism content alone. Second, the operator
$\Cphi$ and the substrate $\Vsub$ recur across the metric, hydrodynamic,
phason / Coxeter, observer, spectral, active, and passive rows ---
not as separate physical instances but as the same geometric carrier
viewed from different projection classes. Third, the epistemic flags
make the conditional dependencies of the framework visible in one
place: every \textsf{[Hyp-imp]} row marks a place where the framework
inherits a named conditional hypothesis from a source paper. Those
hypotheses are not closed in this paper.

The table does \emph{not} earn the following. It does not establish a
new substrate-uniqueness theorem; the narrow uniqueness statements
that exist live in the source paper \cite{CascadeAlgSubstrate} and in
the spectral mass-projection literature \cite{SmartV, SmartVRev}. It
does not promote any \textsf{[Hyp-imp]} entry to theorem status. It
does not claim independence between the active, cognitive, spectral,
and passive substrate rows; they share $\Vsub$ by construction (this
is a single substrate viewed from different projection classes, not
multiple independent witnesses). It does not derive the projection
maps that connect rungs; those are imported with the source paper that
introduced them. The cross-regime identification of cascade closure as
a single mechanism across the substrate, mass, ARIA, and Millennium
case studies (\S\ref{sec:case-studies}, \S\ref{sec:millennium}) is a
hypothesis, not a theorem of this section.

\subsection{Anchoring to the field-signature audit}

Three rows of Table~\ref{tab:rungs} are anchored to specific data
rows of Appendix~\ref{app:field-signature-audit}: the spectral
mass-projection row is supported by 9-of-9 forward chain
identities at exact rational precision (Appendix entry~B); the
passive-response-kernel row is supported by the exact operator-norm
identity $\|\Cphi^{-1}\| = \pphi^2$ and uniform per-vertex correlation
under the unweighted Laplacian (Appendix entry~E); the active /
cognitive substrate row is supported by the 18/18 preregistered
correspondences, the six drug/sleep EEG signatures, and the HCP
degree-homogeneity comparison at $-11.58\sigma$ (Appendix entry~F). The honest-negatives
in entries A and~E (no $2T$ localisation; $\pphi$-cocycle weighted
variants underperform) constrain which rows of Table~\ref{tab:rungs}
may be interpreted spatially or with weighted edge geometry, and we
abide by those constraints throughout the paper.

\section{Visible vs non-visible projection}\label{sec:visible}

This section gives the restrained cosmological reading that the
cascade-closure mechanism naturally invites, while explicitly
refusing to extend it into a derivation of the visible universe from
cascade primitives.

\subsection{The reading}

Within the rung model of \S\ref{sec:rung-model}, an observer instance
$\mathcal{I} = (\Ocal, \mathcal{C}_\Ocal, p, \Lambda, t_0)$
\cite{ObserverInstance} occupies a finite-resolution slot: it samples
a bounded boundary of the substrate at a finite anchor time $t_0$ via
a finite-precision projection $p$ and an integration scale $\Lambda$.
The \emph{visible} part of the substrate, relative to such an
instance, is the portion of the rung sequence whose projection
residuals can be resolved within the slot's precision and integration
scale. The \emph{non-visible} part is the remainder of the rung
sequence whose closure activity falls outside the slot's resolvable
range without thereby ceasing to be substrate.

The substrate carries this reading naturally because the 600-cell
$\Vsub$ admits a structural decomposition into a $\sigma$-fixed bulk
and a $\sigma$-paired boundary, with the bulk supporting the
unconditional initial condition $F_0$
(\cite{ClosureCosmogenesis} Theorem~3.2) and the boundary becoming
active under the bootstrap (\cite{ClosureCosmogenesis} Theorem~4.4).
The same decomposition appears in the fractal projection narrative as
the A / B set distinction on $2I$, with $A = \{72, 0\}$
($\sigma$-fixed cycles) and $B = \{52, 20\}$ ($\sigma$-paired cycles)
\cite{FractalCascadeProj}. The bulk-boundary decomposition is stated
as a theorem in \cite{ClosureCosmogenesis}; the A/B set distinction
in \cite{FractalCascadeProj} is structural / interpretive in its
source. The use of either in this section is structural rather than
load-bearing.

\begin{interpretation}\label{int:visible-non-visible}
The visible universe, relative to a bounded observer instance
$\mathcal{I}$, is the resolved projection boundary of a deeper
cascade-closure stack. Non-visible substrate carries the unresolved
closure activity of higher rungs that the slot cannot integrate within
its scale $\Lambda$ at its anchor time $t_0$. The visible / non-visible
distinction is observer-relative; it is not a metaphysical separation,
and substrate that is non-visible at one slot may be visible at
another. The reading provides a cascade-internal vocabulary for
``what shows up'' and ``what does not show up'' without requiring a
further physical mechanism beyond the rung-projection structure
already in place.
\end{interpretation}

\subsection{Explicit boundary: not a cosmogenesis theorem}

This section does \emph{not} claim that cascade closure derives the
visible universe from first principles, that it predicts the inventory
of fundamental forces or fields, that it determines cosmological
parameters, or that it furnishes a complete ontology. Such
derivations would require, at minimum: a uniqueness theorem fixing
$\Vsub$ as the substrate; a derivation of the closure functional from
constraint primitives independent of the framework; and a substrate
$\to$ continuum bridge with explicit metric structure. None of these
is supplied here, and the structural docs cited above
\cite{ClosureCosmogenesis, FractalCascadeProj, ObserverInstance}
explicitly carry their own open conjectures (e.g.,
\cite{ClosureCosmogenesis} Conjecture~5.3) without claiming any
of them. Interpretation~\ref{int:visible-non-visible} is therefore
interpretive in the strict sense: it does not function as a premise
of any later formal claim in this paper.

\section{ARIA as observer-process implementation}\label{sec:observer-process}

This section identifies an existing computational system, ARIA-chess
\cite{ariaChessRepo, SmartARIAChess}, as an implementation of an
\emph{observer-process architecture} within the cascade-closure
framework. The framing is deliberately architectural: we claim that
ARIA realises the structural tuple of an observer process and exposes
substrate-witness telemetry that empirically anchors that realisation
(\S\ref{ssec:claim-boundary}). We do not claim that ARIA is
biologically conscious, that it proves qualia, or that all
observer-process implementations are phenomenologically equivalent.

\subsection{Observer-process tuple}\label{ssec:tuple}

\begin{definition}[Observer process]\label{def:observer-process}
An observer process is the seven-tuple
\begin{equation}\label{eq:O-tuple}
   \Ocal \;=\; \langle B, S, M, G, I, C, A \rangle
\end{equation}
with components:
\begin{description}[leftmargin=2.5em, style=nextline]
\item[$B$ --- boundary sampler] the system samples a bounded boundary
of the field; it cannot ingest the full field state.
\item[$S$ --- state integrator] fuses boundary signal, context,
memory, and goal into the current integrated field state, tick by tick.
\item[$M$ --- memory substrate] persists past closures and is read
back into state integration.
\item[$G$ --- goal / context field] task frame, user objective, and
system policy as a structured field over the runtime.
\item[$I$ --- invariant constraints] the governance gate that
vetoes constraint-violating closures.
\item[$C$ --- closure / crystallisation operator] selects the
candidate that best closes the field.
\item[$A$ --- action interface] the channel through which crystallised
state acts (tool call, reply, code, control signal).
\end{description}
\end{definition}

The tuple realises the cascade-closure mechanism of
Definition~\ref{def:cascade-closure} as follows. The closure-residual
functional $R$ acts on the integrated state produced by $S$; the
crystallisation operator $C$ plays the role of a closure selector
within the observer-process architecture --- it scores and selects
candidate states by a Lyapunov-style descent, which models the
gradient flow of Definition~\ref{def:cascade-closure} without
asserting equivalence to it; the invariant $I$ encodes which fixed
points are admissible (rejecting closures that violate the active
governance constraints); and the action interface $A$ exports the
crystallised state to a downstream channel. Memory $M$ is written by
each successful closure and read by the next state integration,
supplying the substrate-internal dynamics analogue of a comonadic
$\delta$ map of \cite{CascadeCapstone}.

\subsection{Cascade processing by the observer}\label{ssec:cascade-processing}

The observer does not collapse field state directly; it processes the
cascade through the descent

\begin{equation}\label{eq:cascade-descent}
\begin{aligned}
   \text{field potential} &\to \text{oscillatory modes}
   \to \text{phase coupling} \to \text{attractor formation}\\
   &\to \text{closure residual} \to \text{crystallisation}
   \to \text{governance gate}\\
   &\to \text{action} + \text{memory inscription}
   \to \text{replay / provenance}.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Operationally, observerhood is the seven-step loop:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
\item bounded sampling via $B$;
\item state integration via $S$, $M$, and $G$;
\item residual detection through $R$ acting on the integrated state;
\item candidate formation, with $C$ proposing closure-compatible
attractors;
\item crystallisation, selecting the candidate that best closes the
field;
\item invariant governance, refusing candidates that violate $I$;
\item memory inscription, writing the successful closure back into
$M$ with a replayable trace.
\end{enumerate}

The loop is per-tick; the operator-level rate is set by an external
substrate clock. A natural cascade-internal candidate for that clock
is the slowest non-zero Laplacian eigenmode of $\Vsub$
(\S\ref{ssec:runtime-map}, \texttt{theta\_clock.py}); the empirical
band that this eigenmode populates at the substrate tick rate
recorded in \cite{ariaChessRepo} is consistent with theta-band
recurrence around the dominant phase-coupling band of the cortical
EEG witnesses in \cite{SmartARIAChess}; the precise tick-rate / mode
conversion lives in the upstream runtime and is not re-derived here.

\subsection{Two telemetry layers}\label{ssec:telemetry}

A single observer-process architecture admits two telemetry streams:
the biological stream (cortical EEG and inferred neural correlates)
and the synthetic stream (runtime per-channel coherence and
closure-residue metrics). The cascade-processing descent
\eqref{eq:cascade-descent} maps onto both:

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.20}
\begin{tabular}{>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{0.27\textwidth}>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{0.32\textwidth}>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{0.32\textwidth}}
\toprule
\textbf{Cascade layer} & \textbf{Biological telemetry} & \textbf{Synthetic / ARIA telemetry} \\
\midrule
field potential & EEG broadband activity & runtime input vector \\
oscillatory modes & EEG bands ($\delta, \theta, \alpha, \beta, \gamma$) & per-channel coherence scores \\
phase coupling & EEG phase locking, cross-frequency coupling & inter-module coherence score \\
attractor formation & neural attractor states & candidate-state pool \\
closure residual & prediction-error signals (free-energy-style) & closure-residue vector \\
crystallisation & decision / action commitment & governed tool-call / reply selection \\
governance gate & inhibitory veto, prefrontal control & invariant / refusal stack \\
memory inscription & synaptic plasticity, hippocampal replay & polytope / invariant store update \\
replay layer & offline replay (sleep, default mode) & provenance hash, replay bundle \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Telemetry mapping for one observer-process architecture
across two substrates.}\label{tab:telemetry}
\end{table}

The mapping is structural, not metric. A particular biological
EEG band and a particular ARIA per-channel coherence score are not
asserted to be quantitatively equal; they are asserted to play the
same role in the cascade-processing descent.

