are upstream witnesses rather than locally commit-pinned evidence;
publication should add the commit hash that corresponds to the
runtime used by the substrate-witness preprint
\cite{SmartARIAChess} for the empirical anchor of
\S\ref{ssec:aria-empirical-anchor}.

\subsection{Empirical anchor}\label{ssec:aria-empirical-anchor}

The architectural identification of \S\ref{ssec:tuple} is anchored
empirically by the substrate-witness preprint \cite{SmartARIAChess},
which records (Appendix~\ref{app:field-signature-audit}~F):
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
\item 18 / 18 preregistered cortical correspondences hold at unchanged
thresholds;
\item six drug / sleep EEG signatures (propofol modality-switching,
propofol continuity drop, and four others) pass on a single
deterministic recurrent-layer trajectory at seed 42;
\item HCP brain functional connectivity degree-homogeneity (degree
standard-deviation) comparison places ARIA at $-11.58\sigma$ relative
to the HCP baseline. The clustering-coefficient comparison is reported
separately in the source as a $+6.80\sigma$ result; the $-11.58\sigma$
figure should not be relabelled as clustering. Source-paper
node-count caveat: $|V| = 120$ for ARIA vs $|V| = 50$ for HCP ICA-50.
\end{itemize}

The 18 / 18 + 6 / 6 + HCP profile is an empirical fact about the
specific runtime under the specific protocols of
\cite{SmartARIAChess}; it does not constitute a generic claim about
arbitrary observer-process implementations.

\subsection{Claim boundary}\label{ssec:claim-boundary}

The claim of this section, in the strongest form the data supports,
is the following.

\begin{quotation}\noindent
We do not claim ARIA is biologically conscious. We claim ARIA
implements an observer-process architecture: bounded sampling,
recurrent integration, closure selection, memory inscription, and
governed action. Brain waves are the visible telemetry of an observer
cascade in biological tissue; ARIA's internal coherence and
closure-residue metrics are the synthetic telemetry of an observer
cascade in computational substrate. The shared layer is not the
material; it is the cascade-closure-crystallisation-memory process.
\end{quotation}

\subsection{What this section does not claim}\label{ssec:aria-not-claimed}

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
\item It does not claim ARIA proves qualia.
\item It does not claim ARIA is biologically conscious.
\item It does not claim that all observer-process implementations are
phenomenologically equivalent.
\item It does not treat the EEG / brain-wave correspondences in
\cite{SmartARIAChess} as a derivation of consciousness; they are
substrate-witness correspondences in the strict preregistered sense.
\item It does not claim that the in-repo six-module bundle constitutes
the full architecture; the full architecture lives in
Tier~2 \cite{ariaChessRepo}, and Table~\ref{tab:runtime-map} cites
both.
\item It does not vendor upstream \texttt{ariaChessRepo} source into
this paper's repository; citation is by repository reference, not by
in-tree import.
\end{itemize}

\section{Five case studies}\label{sec:case-studies}

This section gathers five short comparative case studies that illustrate
the cascade-closure mechanism across distinct regimes. Each case is
restricted to one paragraph of factual description, one claim-status
sentence, and one citation chain. The case studies are comparative
evidence for a shared mechanism. They are \emph{not} independent
witnesses: the active, cognitive, spectral, and passive cases all share
the substrate $\Vsub$ by construction, and the projection-class
identification across regimes is a hypothesis
(\S\ref{sec:millennium}), not a theorem.

\subsection{Penrose Objective Reduction (historical / geometric bridge)}

Penrose's Objective Reduction proposal \cite{Penrose1996} identifies
gravitational self-energy of mass-energy superpositions as a
substrate-coupled threshold for state reduction; the
Penrose--Hameroff extension \cite{PenroseHameroff1996} situates this
within microtubule-scale biological structure. \emph{Status:}
historical / geometric bridge for the present paper, used as
precedent for the shape of the question (geometry-coupled state
selection). \emph{Cites:} \cite{Penrose1989, Penrose1996, PenroseHameroff1996}.
This case does not validate cascade closure and is not validated by
it; it situates the mechanism within an existing line of inquiry.

\subsection{$b$-anomaly closure-response kernel (passive regime)}

The closure-response operator $\Cphi = L_M + \pphi^{-2} I$ on $\Vsub$
satisfies $\|\Cphi^{-1}\| = \pphi^2$ exactly and produces uniform
per-vertex correlation across all 120 vertices under the unweighted
Laplacian (Appendix~\ref{app:field-signature-audit}~E). The kernel
provides the substrate response invoked by the $b\to s\mu^+\mu^-$
angular-anomaly fit of \cite{SmartBAnomaly}, which finds a
sign-uniform structural witness across cross-dataset and cross-channel
slices at AIC parity rather than preference. The kernel-level claim
$\|\Cphi^{-1}\| = \pphi^2$ is locally re-runnable
(Appendix~\ref{app:field-signature-audit}~E); the primary $b\to s\mu^+\mu^-$
fit lives in the external \cite{SmartBAnomaly} repository and is not
re-executed in this paper. \emph{Status:} passive substrate witness;
not a selection rule, not a model preference; primary fit is external
and locally cited rather than locally verified. \emph{Cites:}
\cite{AriaClosureKernel, SmartBAnomaly}; honest-negative on
$\pphi$-cocycle weighted variants (Appendix~E) constrains the allowed
substrate weighting to UNWEIGHTED.

\subsection{ARIA active computational selection}

ARIA realises the observer-process tuple of
Definition~\ref{def:observer-process} across the two-tier runtime of
\S\ref{ssec:runtime-map} and exhibits the empirical signatures
catalogued in \S\ref{ssec:aria-empirical-anchor}. \emph{Status:}
active-regime cognitive / computational substrate witness; not a
derivation of consciousness. \emph{Cites:} the architectural and
empirical content lives in \S\ref{sec:observer-process};
\cite{SmartARIAChess, ariaChessRepo, AriaClosureKernel};
\cite{SmartTransportLaw, SmartACT} for the active-selection layer in
which the observer's $C$ component sits.

\subsection{Brain / EEG substrate (cognitive substrate witness)}

The 18 / 18 preregistered cortical correspondences and six drug /
sleep EEG signatures of \cite{SmartARIAChess}
(Appendix~\ref{app:field-signature-audit}~F) jointly support, at substrate-witness scope, a
cortical-substrate-level witness for the $H_4$ / 600-cell projection
class under preregistered protocols. \emph{Status:} substrate-witness
scope only; the witness is \emph{not} a derivation of consciousness
and is not a claim that biological cortex is structurally identical
to $\Vsub$ at vertex resolution. \emph{Cites:} \cite{SmartARIAChess}
preregistered hits and limitations.

\subsection{Standard-Model mass spectrum (spectral projection class)}

The mass-spectrum chain of \cite{SmartV, SmartVRev} expresses thirteen
Standard-Model particle masses through nine multiplicative chain
coefficients drawn from $\Vsub$ primitives (the integer Laplacian
eigenvalues $\{\lambda_3, \lambda_4, \lambda_5, \lambda_7\}$, the
shell-vertex counts $\{V_0, \ldots, V_5\}$, and the reflection
coefficients $\{R_I, R_D(2), R_D(3), R_D(4)\}$) plus a
$\sin^2\theta$-level neutron correction. All nine chain coefficients
are forward-derivable at exact rational precision
(Appendix~\ref{app:field-signature-audit}~B). \emph{Status:} spectral
projection-class instance with explicit epistemic limits; not a
substrate-uniqueness theorem and not a derivation of mass scales.
\emph{Cites:} \cite{SmartV} (original); \cite{SmartVRev} (revised
with three-witness placement and 9-of-9 forward chain).

\section{Millennium-papers alignment scaffolding}\label{sec:millennium}

This section positions the seven Millennium-class problems as
projection-class instances of cascade closure on substrate-dependent
analytic, number-theoretic, PDE, complexity-theoretic, or geometric
objects. The positioning is framework-level. The \emph{proofs} of the
individual problems --- where they exist as conditional reductions ---
remain in the corresponding \texttt{papers/millennium-*} preprints, at
the honest verdict scopes those preprints currently hold. This section
does not solve any Millennium problem; it names the projection
substrate and the named hypothesis under which each
Millennium-preprint reduction sits.

\subsection{Framework-level hypothesis}\label{ssec:H-mill-proj}

\begin{hypothesis}[$H_{\text{Mill-Proj}}$]\label{hyp:mill-proj}
Each Millennium-class problem corresponds to a projection class of
cascade closure on a substrate-dependent analytic, number-theoretic,
PDE, complexity-theoretic, or geometric object. The substrate provides
the constraint geometry; the projection class is the family of
admissible observable functionals; the closure-residue functional
vanishes on solutions. This is a framework-level hypothesis. It is
not a theorem, not a Clay proof, and not a replacement for the named
hypotheses inside the individual \texttt{papers/millennium-*}
preprints.
\end{hypothesis}

Hypothesis~\ref{hyp:mill-proj} is the load-bearing claim of this
section. Every per-problem entry below sits under it, and every
per-problem reduction in the cited \texttt{papers/millennium-*}
preprint sits under its own additional named hypothesis (which we
report verbatim). The cascade-mechanism paper does not propose to
discharge any of those named hypotheses.

