The verdict-scope letters follow the
\texttt{project\_millennium\_scope\_pass} convention: $\delta$ is a
honest reformulation under named hypothesis (the cascade reduction is
correct, but the load-bearing hypothesis is equivalent to the
classical problem); $\beta$ is a bridge layer (the cascade gives a
spectral / structural framework whose continuum lift is open);
$\gamma$ is a restricted-model separation; \emph{coherence} is a
compatibility statement with respect to an already-proved classical
result.

\subsection{Give-the-game-away requirements}\label{ssec:give-the-game}

For Millennium-class preprints to land as natural instances of
$H_{\text{Mill-Proj}}$ rather than as separate strange claims, the
present section must satisfy four operational requirements.

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
\item State $H_{\text{Mill-Proj}}$ explicitly as in
\S\ref{ssec:H-mill-proj}. (Done.)
\item Name each per-problem hypothesis in the source preprint's
current notation: $H_{\sigma\text{-fix}}$ for RH;
$H_{\text{OS-lift}}$ for YM; $B_{BSD,\text{conv}}$,
$B_{BSD,\text{rank}}$, $B_{BSD,\text{spec}}$ for BSD; $H_1$, $H_{NS}$,
$B_{NS}$, $H_{P6/P7}$ for NS; $H_{4a}$, $H_{4a}^{\text{alg}}$ for Hodge;
$H_{\sigma\text{-irr-NP}}$, $B_{\sigma\text{-P}}$, and
\texttt{Conj.~completeness} for PNP; P5 and C2.bis for Poincar\'e.
(Done in Table~\ref{tab:millennium}.)
\item State, per problem, in one sentence which substrate the
projection sits on. (Column 2 of Table~\ref{tab:millennium}.)
\item Refuse to prove any per-problem statement. The reductions remain
in the corresponding \texttt{papers/millennium-*} preprints; this
section cites and positions, it does not derive.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Honest verdict-scope discipline}\label{ssec:verdict-discipline}

The cascade-mechanism paper must reproduce the source verdict scopes
without upgrade. The allowed claim is

\begin{quotation}\noindent
The cascade-mechanism paper positions the current
\texttt{papers/millennium-*} preprints as projection-class instances
under $H_{\text{Mill-Proj}}$ and names the hypotheses on which their
individual reductions depend.
\end{quotation}

\noindent The disallowed claim is ``the cascade mechanism resolves
the Millennium problems''. We do not write this. We do not imply it
through choice of phrasing, through omission of conditional flags, or
through suggestive section headers.

\subsection{Drop-order coordination}\label{ssec:drop-order}

The intended drop order, conditional on the cascade-mechanism paper
landing first as framework-positioning prerequisite reading, is:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
\item This cascade-mechanism paper.
\item \texttt{papers/millennium-rh-formal/rh-formal.tex} (most-developed; the
$\sigma$ / $\tau_{\rm crit}$ reformulation has the strongest standalone
substrate witness).
\item Yang--Mills (octonion derivation-algebra substrate; discrete
spectral gap is concrete; $H_{\text{OS-lift}}$ remains explicit).
\item Birch--Swinnerton-Dyer (Rankin--Selberg / Hecke substrate; bridge
axioms remain open).
\item Navier--Stokes / Hodge / P vs NP / Poincar\'e in whatever order
their respective preprints reach the publication standard required by
their domains.
\end{enumerate}

The Millennium preprints, on publication, should cite this paper as
their framework-positioning prerequisite. This is a coordination
arrangement, not a publishing claim.

\subsection{Cite-only, do-not-derive}\label{ssec:cite-only}

The principle of this section is to cite, not to derive. Some
non-load-bearing prose from the programme docs
\texttt{docs/rh-cascade-closure-dynamics.md} and
\texttt{docs/rh-projection-class.md} may be absorbed into the
introductory paragraph of \S\ref{ssec:seven-mill} for narrative
continuity, but the load-bearing mathematical content stays in the
corresponding Millennium preprints. No theorem in this section is
stronger than $H_{\text{Mill-Proj}}$, and $H_{\text{Mill-Proj}}$ is
itself a hypothesis.

